The Senate Committee on Finance offered the following
substitute to HB 79:
A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
AN ACT
1 To amend Title 48 of the Official Code of Georgia Annotated, relating to revenue and
2 taxation, so as to provide for a tax credit for certain eligible expenses incurred for firearm
3 safe handling instructional courses; to provide for an aggregate annual cap; to provide for
4 definitions; to provide for terms and conditions; to provide for credit preapproval by the
5 department; to prohibit the creation of certain lists or databases; to provide for rules and
6 regulations; to exempt sales of firearms, ammunition, gun safes, and related accessories from
7 sales and use taxes during a four-day period each year; to provide for automatic repeals; to
8 provide for related matters; to provide for a short title; to provide for effective dates and
9 applicability; to repeal conflicting laws; and for other purposes.
10 BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF GEORGIA:
11 PART I
12 SECTION 1-1.
13 This part shall be known and may be cited as the "Firearm Safe Handling Tax Credit Act."
- 1 -

25 LC 50 1264S
14 SECTION 1-2.
15 Title 48 of the Official Code of Georgia Annotated, relating to revenue and taxation, is
16 amended by adding a new Code section to read as follows:
17 "48-7-29.11A.
18 (a) As used in this Code section, the term:
19 (1) 'Eligible expenses' means expenses incurred by an individual taxpayer during the
20 taxable year for the cost of a firearm safe handling instructional course.
21 (2) 'Firearm' means any handgun, shotgun, rifle, or other weapon that will be converted
22 or is designed to or may readily be converted to expel single or multiple projectiles by
23 action of an explosion of a combustible material.
24 (3) 'Firearm safe handling instructional course' means an in-person training of at least
25 two hours in duration that includes, but is not limited to, instruction on safe handling, use,
26 and storage of firearms.
27 (b)(1) Under the terms and conditions of this Code section, an individual taxpayer shall
28 be allowed a credit against the tax imposed by Code Section 48-7-20 in the amount of
29 such taxpayer's eligible expenses or $300.00, whichever is less.
30 (2) In no event shall the aggregate limit of tax credits allowed under this Code section
31 for any year exceed $10 million.
32 (c)(1) The department shall develop a procedure to be followed in the preapproval of any
33 tax credit allowed pursuant to this Code section.
34 (2) An individual taxpayer seeking a tax credit pursuant to this Code section shall apply
35 to the department for preapproval of such tax credit. Such taxpayer shall specify the
36 taxable year for which he or she is seeking a tax credit.
37 (3) Individual taxpayers that properly apply for preapproval of such tax credit following
38 the procedure developed by the department shall be approved on a first-come, first served
39 basis until the aggregate limit for such tax credits is reached for that year.
